Summary: How to do wormhole jumps in Frontier
Keywords: wormholes
X-News-Reader: VMS NEWS 1.24



What I give here below is a brief description of the use of the
"wormhole" method and the -basic- "wormhole" equations.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

 A "wormhole" jump-point is a location that is an intermediate
position in a 2-step jump sequence;
(start-point) to (wormhole jump-point) to (end-point).

 The -basic- wormhole formulae will produce the ideal coordinates
for a -pair- of wormhole jump-points; you can use either or both locations.
 The actual jump-points are found where there are any star-systems to
jump to that are within the range of the ideal wormhole jump-point;
you should choose the jump-point that gives the best fuel economy
from the available star-systems around the ideal location.

 These equations are a subset of a more general (more difficult)
set of equations. The basic set is most useful for the local/nearby
explored region of space. (The general equations come into play when
going out more than several hundred light-years... I'll post those also
if there's enough interest. Let me know.)

------------------------------------------------------------------------
Let us begin:(as simply as possible)

 For star-systems at coordinates (X,Y) and (U,V),

 Let   a = (U-X)/2 
       b = (V-Y)/2
       m = Mid-range distance
           (a^2 + b^2)^(1/2) ; m equals the square-root of the sum
                                 of [a-squared plus b-squared]

 Use a wormhole distance Wn, defined as follows:
 |
 |  Let:
 |      W = base Wormhole-distance
 |        = 81.92 sector-lengths (=655.36 Light-years)
 |
 |  So then:
 |      Wn = Wormhole-distance-of-order-n
 |         = n*W       ;n-fold multiple of the base Wormhole-distance W
 |         = n*(81.92)
 |  Note: you are free to choose the value of n *PROVIDED* that Wn is
 |        greater than half of the distance between your starting and ending
 |        star-systems; typically you will just use W1 for nearby systems.


 Let   S = Shift-distance
         = (W^2 - m^2)^(1/2)

 then  A = aS/m ;upper-case symbols (A,B) are different from (a,b)
       B = bS/m


 RESULT: THE WORMHOLE IDEAL-NEIGHBORHOOD COORDINATES (WX,WY)
 (remember that a -pair- of ideal locations is produced)

         WX = X+a+B, WY = Y+b-A
 and
         WX = X+a-B, WY = Y+b+A.

 EXAMPLES:
 (fuel usage is shown for a class 8 hyperdrive, as an upper limit)
 (* indicates the preferred choice of jump-point)

 Sol(0.0,0.2)-Phekda(1.5,5.0)/
 ideals=        findings=             stepwise class-8 Fuel-usage (tons)
 (78.9,-21.8)   Esszeand (78.7,-22.1) *(7+11=18)
 (-77.4,27.0)   ...desolate-region

 Sol(0.0,0.2)-Cemiess(-1.5,-2.5)/
 ideals=        findings=             stepwise class-8 Fuel-usage (tons)
 (70.8,-40.9)   Uressmi (70.0,-41.9)  *(4+7=11)
 (-72.3,38.6)   Vephied (-71.7,39.4)  *(7+4=11)

 Cemiess(-1.5,-2.5)-Phekda(1.5,5.0)/
 ideals=        findings=             stepwise class-8 Fuel-usage (tons)
 (76.0,-29.0)   Essface (76,-29.5)      (14+7=21)
 (-76.0,31.6)   Exdain (-75.8,31.7)   *(4+11=15)

 and, by a basic 2nd-order wormhole W2,
                                                            class-8
 Sol(0.0,0.2)-Beta Lyrae(-146.25,85.2)/Vewaay(-143.4,-78.4) fuel=(7+14=21) 

 ...read this verbally as:
 "Sol(#,#) to Beta Lyrae(#,#) by-way-of Vewaay(#,#)"
                              (via)

 If you have the patience to search around the ideal-neighborhood a bit,
 then you can usually find a total fuel-usage solution that amounts to about
 1/4 or less of your maximum range fuel-usage. If not, then try a larger
 wormhole-distance-order (multiple of the basic W=81.92 sector-lengths).

 This will get you from anywhere to anywhere - so explore!
 (For practice, try to land in the Pleiades system (32,32).)


 Final note:
 Within the theme of the game, I'd like this feature to be kept in
 the game in some way - possibly as a provision of a "wormhole resonator
 unit" equipment-modification to the hyperdrive... not more heavy, just
 more expensive in accordance with the range multiples.... 


-Hawkins
