Well actually, I just figured out how to *reliably* put a class 7 drive in my
Trader last night. However, the method involved some degree of long term 
planning!!

Simply conduct your normal business, but only service equipment NOT the drive,
after about 1 year game time (approx 50 jumps) the drive will fail. The drive
will fail *on arrival* to your chosen destination, with interplanetary
capability still useable. If you're in a high tech system, just fly on in as
normal, land/dock and buy yourself a class 7! If you happen to be in
hicksville at the time, just restore your last save, and jump to the nearest
high tech system, reloading until the drive fails again (it seems to be
statistically weighted with age of drive). Took me about 10 jumps to reproduce
the failure.

Unfortunately, this is only the start of your problems, a class 7 drive is
*BIG*, throw away that 20MW laser, whittle down those shields. I've calculated
useable tonnage for everything (goodies + cargo), assuming what I consider to
be bare minimum (i.e. Drive + enough fuel for one max range Jump), for both
Couriers and Traders (normal and '+' configurations):

    Courier:    Class 5 drive (10.41 ly):    350-150-25t = 175t
                Class 6 drive (15.00 ly):    350-250-36t =  64t

    Trader:     Class 6 drive (10.28 ly):    525-250-36t = 239t
                Class 7 drive (14.00 ly):    525-400-49t =  76t !!

I guess you could say that Couriers/Traders weren't designed with an upgrade
path in mind. Also there is virtually no point in running a 'Trader+'
when you could use a 'Courier+' (except that it looks better IMHO). Courier+
is faster, cheaper with greater jump range for the loss of only 12t capacity.

I was beginning to wish for greater jump range, but I think anything else in
the game looks like a shoe box in comparsion to the Imperial ships. At least
now I have some options.

Hope that helps,

Iain.

