In article <1993Dec1.234518.50497@frodo.cc.flinders.edu.au>, Phil Kernick writes:

> In the same orbital map I can see a small blue dot.  It moves around when
> you reorient the map with the mouse, but it doesn't seem to be in a constant
> place.  I originally thought that it was my current ship position, but it
> doesn't actually seem to be that.  The manual makes no mention of it.  Any
> ideas?

There are two kinds of small circles, one is yourself, the other one is for
hyperspace  clouds.   When  you  arrive,  accelerate,  take out the map and
scroll the time-axis, then you can see you moving away from the cloud.

There  are also unlabeled +'s, which represent other ships.  You can target
them and use a radar mapper to identify them, or fire up the autopilot.

This is especially useful when you do an assassination mission and arrive a
few  hours too late in the system where the enemy lifts off.  You then take
out  the map, zoom to the starport/spacestation, and target every spaceship
near  to  it.   Often you still find your enemy, although you're 10 or more
AU's  away.   Keep  it  in  the  radar  mapper and wait for the information
disappear - now the enemy went through hyperspace.  Pause the game, and use
the  Cloud  Analyser to find out his destination (the Analyser works 50% of
all  cases  on  that  large  distance),  and  you can probably complete the
mission although you were far too late.

> I currently am running an Asp Explorer and am thinking of trading up to an
> Imperial Courier.  Is it worth it?

No,  as  long  as you don't do trading, I strongly recommend a Constrictor.
It's  small  (hard  to  hit)  compared to the Courier, it's faster, and has
enough  cargo  to  hold  29 tonnes of fuel (about 3 jumps  15 lightyears),
although  being  equiped to do missions and beat any enemy if you're not an
absolute  beginner in combat.  I get killed with it about 1% of all fights,
most  times  because  I was smoking a cigarette or drinking something while
the "Ship is under attack" message appeared and therefore had no hands free
to disable the autopilot early enough...  ;^)

