:   Have any of you seen Privateer or xwing?
:   That's what frontier combat should have been like!
:   If only.....

      No way.

      I played both Privateer and Frontier (I have a PC and an Amiga
      mind you :-)) and Privateer doesn't even come close to Frontier.
      The only thing Privateer has is "intelligent missions" (ala Wing
      Commander). But once you're through with them, you sell your
      game. Not so with Frontier. Not to mention the breathtaking space
      flight mechanism in Frontier, whereas Privateer won't even let
      you approach a base or a planet.

      Being both an Amiga and a PC player, I'm beginning to have some
      understanding of what sort of games are expected on
      these two machines. Frontier has gone almost completely
      unnoticed on PC (the cs.ibm.pc.games group hardly contains one message
      per day about it). PC players want well beta-tested, polished,
      straightforward games. Amiga players are more demanding
      (probably because the game industry is older on Amiga than PC)
      and a masterpice like Frontier is appreciated to its true value.
      PC gamers will only see the bugs and declare the game
      uninteresting. Sad.

      I suspect PC players will reach one day the maturity of Amiga
      ones one day (and I really don't mean to sound superior here, I
      enjoy PC games as well as Amiga's). This seems to be the trend
      as demonstrated by the Wing Commander / XWing / Privateer series
      (from the best to the worst).


